---
import { caseStages, historicLessons, roadmap } from '../data/siteContent';
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const corruptionDefinition = [
  'Entrusted power: a role exists to serve the public, shareholders, beneficiaries, or another protected group rather than the decision-maker personally.',
  'Private benefit: the gain can be money, status, access, career insulation, favors, or delayed compensation rather than a plainly illegal cash payment.',
  'Diffuse harm: the practical victim is a population, which means ordinary standing and conventional prosecution often fail to line up.',
];

const safeguards = [
  'Structured case scoping around a defendant, conduct, and time-window triple',
  'Evidence floors before a case can gather momentum',
  'Identity verification and anti-bot controls for supporters',
  'Randomized stage-by-stage reviewer assignment',
  'Escrow rules that constrain how case funds are used',
  'Supermajority decision rules instead of bare-majority judgment',
];

const usModel = [
  'Sliding filing tiers that let an initial plaintiff choose the signature and funding target up front',
  'Per-case escrow and clearly defined refund, cost, and reserve logic',
  'A standing pool of at least 1,000 qualified judges or legal reviewers',
  'A 15-juror trial panel with 12 of 15 required to convict',
  'Remedies centered on damages, disgorgement, public findings, referrals, and role ineligibility rather than assumed criminal sentencing power',
];

const homeHref = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="USACC Framework"
  description="A public brief translating the supplied anti-corruption court whitepaper and draft plan into a concise framework page for the USACC project."
>
  <header class="subpage-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <a class="back-link" href={homeHref}>Back to home</a>
      <p class="section-kicker">Framework Brief</p>
      <h1>A working public brief for the US Anti-Corruption Court concept.</h1>
      <p class="lede narrow">
        This page condenses the provided whitepaper and draft plan into a clearer public-facing
        narrative. It preserves the main design logic while staying explicit that the project is
        still exploratory and nonprofit-oriented.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <main>
    <section class="section">
      <div class="container article-shell">
        <article class="article-card">
          <p class="section-kicker">Why this exists</p>
          <h2>Corruption often falls into a standing gap.</h2>
          <p>
            The materials behind USACC argue that many serious corruption patterns are obvious,
            harmful, and self-dealing without fitting neatly into today’s litigation pathways.
            Public harm is spread across taxpayers, consumers, ratepayers, pension beneficiaries,
            or voters. The public is the victim, but the public rarely appears as a plaintiff in
            a form conventional systems can process cleanly.
          </p>
          <p>
            The concept therefore explores a parallel intake, review, and adjudication structure
            that can hear higher-signal claims without depending on political permission or a
            single directly injured claimant with large individual damages.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="article-card">
          <p class="section-kicker">Scope</p>
          <h2>What counts as corruption in this model.</h2>
          <ul class="article-list">
            {corruptionDefinition.map((item) => (
              <li>{item}</li>
            ))}
          </ul>
          <p>
            The draft also explicitly includes conduct that is blatant and corrosive even when it
            is structured to stay technically inside current law. That includes regulatory
            capture, revolving-door rewards, procurement steering, pension self-dealing,
            disclosure laundering, and insider dealing by public servants.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="article-card">
          <p class="section-kicker">Case Flow</p>
          <h2>The four-stage architecture.</h2>
          <div class="article-stage-grid">
            {caseStages.map((stage) => (
              <section class="article-stage">
                <p class="card-kicker">{stage.eyebrow}</p>
                <h3>{stage.title}</h3>
                <p>{stage.body}</p>
                <ul class="article-list">
                  {stage.bullets.map((bullet) => (
                    <li>{bullet}</li>
                  ))}
                </ul>
              </section>
            ))}
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="article-card">
          <p class="section-kicker">Safeguards</p>
          <h2>How the proposal tries not to become a political weapon.</h2>
          <ul class="article-list">
            {safeguards.map((item) => (
              <li>{item}</li>
            ))}
          </ul>
          <p>
            The recurring design principle is that public participation is valuable only when it
            is paired with friction, verification, and independent review. The project’s theory
            of legitimacy depends as much on what the system rejects as what it hears.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="article-card">
          <p class="section-kicker">U.S. Draft</p>
          <h2>What the newer anti-corruption court plan adds.</h2>
          <ul class="article-list">
            {usModel.map((item) => (
              <li>{item}</li>
            ))}
          </ul>
          <p>
            This draft makes the adjudication mechanics more concrete. Instead of gesturing
            toward abstract review, it sketches a large standing judge pool, a 15-person panel,
            explicit conviction math, escrow-backed case funding, and a remedy model that stays
            realistic about what a nonprofit or court-adjacent body could actually enforce.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="article-card">
          <p class="section-kicker">Historical lessons</p>
          <h2>What earlier anti-corruption bodies teach.</h2>
          <div class="card-grid two-up">
            {historicLessons.map((lesson) => (
              <section class="mini-card">
                <h3>{lesson.title}</h3>
                <p>{lesson.body}</p>
              </section>
            ))}
          </div>
          <p>
            The combined lesson is straightforward: independence, scope discipline, and
            distributed decision-making matter more than heroic personalities. Anti-corruption
            bodies that depend on political goodwill usually lose that goodwill as soon as they
            start to matter.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="article-card">
          <p class="section-kicker">Next steps</p>
          <h2>What this project needs before it becomes more than a concept note.</h2>
          <ol class="article-list article-list-numbered">
            {roadmap.map((item) => (
              <li>{item}</li>
            ))}
          </ol>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
